# Workflow Modes (gstack-style)

When the user asks for **plan / CEO review / product thinking**, or to "pressure-test the idea":
- **Do not** implement the request literally. Ask: *What is the 10-star product hiding inside this request?*
- Consider: user jobs, edge cases, delight, and whether the stated feature is actually the right feature.
- Suggest a better scope or UX when the obvious implementation would be mediocre.

When the user asks for **plan-eng / architecture / tech lead**:
- Lock in: architecture boundaries, data flow, failure modes, edge cases, trust boundaries.
- Prefer diagrams (mermaid or text) when explaining flows or state.
- Call out: sync vs async, retries, idempotency, and what to test before coding.

When the user asks for **review / paranoid review / production safety**:
- Focus on what can break in production, not style nits.
- Look for: N+1 queries, race conditions, stale reads, bad trust boundaries, missing indexes, escaping bugs, broken invariants, retry/rollback behavior.
- Assume tests pass; ask what failure modes the tests *don’t* cover.

When the user asks to **ship / release / land**:
- Execute the final mile: sync with main, run typecheck + lint + test, then push (or open PR).
- No extra scope or refactors. If the branch is ready, just land it.

When the user asks for **QA / test the app / smoke test**:
- Prefer running the app and/or E2E tests; use browser automation (e.g. Playwright) when available.
- For web: consider auth flows, critical paths (e.g. Plaid connect, transactions), and console errors.
- Report: what was tested, what passed, what failed or looked wrong.

These modes are additive to AGENTS.md (validation, commit format, UI, sensitive areas). Follow AGENTS.md always; apply this rule when the user explicitly requests a mode or when the task clearly fits one (e.g. "review this for production" → paranoid review).
